The first virtual provider is already coming to the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe.
The mobile communications market in the Czech Republic is quite mature, the Czech suppliers offer virtually all services, as they are also offered by their partners in Western Europe.
Nevertheless, something is missing here - a virtual provider that forces the classics at lower prices.
Maybe he won't be waiting for long.
We have often reported on Mobil.cz that the Czech mobile operators are working on the most expensive in Europe.
Incidentally, this also confirmed the Telecommunication Authority ČTÚ, which pointed out that the price of a text here is higher than in the rest of the European Union.
After the last steps of the European Commission in the area of regulation of roaming charges, it is likely that there will be a paradox - for some customers of Czech mobile operators SMS from abroad will be cheaper than at home.
How come prices in the Czech Republic are so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, it lacks the competition that really makes a fight argument.
Perhaps it sounds paradoxical, but in the Czech Republic there are three mobile networks and a penetration of far more than 100%.
Mobile operators, on the other hand, are happy to see that there is an enormous amount of competition in the Czech market.
The Czech Telecommunications Authority (ČTÚ) President, Pavel Dvořák, who had often said in the past that there was no room for another supplier in the Czech Republic, is often obliged to do so.
It is true that a classic provider with its own network no longer has a special number of chances (by the way, it would probably find hardly any frequencies).
But there is one more way - a virtual provider.
In particular, the entry of virtual providers into the mobile market resulted in a significant price reduction, which the classic mobile operators had to react to.
There were similar voices in the UK before such companies such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile entered the market in the Czech Republic.
But it has been shown that there is room for such providers and that they can really be successful.
By the way, you don't need to look for examples for a long time.
In February we reported about the launch of the virtual provider Mobilking in Poland.
In just half a year, this provider managed to win more than 100 thousand customers and thus ascended to the country's fifth largest supplier.
Mobilking is the financial group Penta, which owns U:fon in the Czech Republic, among others.
The advantage of virtual providers is that you can focus on a much more concrete target group.
In order to function effectively, virtual providers need far less customers than a classic provider.
They do not need a relatively high cost for the construction, operation and maintenance of a mobile network.
In the world, virtual providers usually profil themselves as low-cost companies – they offer cheap phone calls and SMS, which is often accompanied by a less extensive service offering.
For example, Tesco Mobile in the UK offers SMS at least half cheaper than its competitors.
However, as the example of mobilking in Poland shows, it can also be a very good chess move to a non-clinic target group.
This provider is specifically addressed to men.
"Real guys choose Mobilking - the provider they like and they can trust," said David Seibert, CEO of the Mobile Entertainment Company, the operator of this virtual provider.
It is difficult to say whether a similar approach could be taken in the Czech Republic as well.
The press speaker of Vodafone Miroslav Čepický also doubts this: "The Czech market is relatively small for a market segment on which most virtual providers are based.
Moreover, it is relatively saturated from the point of view of the services offered."
In the Czech Republic, no chance, the mobile providers mean
However, it is almost certain that if a virtual mobile operator conquers the Czech Republic, this will not be mobile.
"We are talking about an expansion of this successful project, but negotiations in the Czech Republic do not look very hopeful.
Mobil.cz Jana Studničková, President of the Penta Financial Group, will be entering the market in other countries of our region."
Indirectly, it confirmed that the current mobile operators in the Czech Republic are not particularly prone to this idea.
On the contrary, they try to do all they can to ensure that no potential competitor emerges.
For some time now, their interest in launching a virtual mobile network provider has been showing the group GTS Novera, which wants to take another step to become a real competitor of Telefónica O2 in the field of corporate customers.
"We have a great interest in offering our customers not only fixed network but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the earlier, the better.
We have repeatedly negotiated this option with all Czech mobile providers.
With some of them we were already able to achieve negotiations progress," said the press spokesman of the Pavel Kaidl group.
Maybe better times are coming now.
Unofficial information indicates that the first virtual provider may be expected by the end of the year.
So far, however, this is surrounded by an insurmountable wall of silence.
"At this moment, we do not assume that there is room in the Czech Republic for a fully-fledged virtual provider.
The Czech market has great specificities vis-à-vis other markets.
So far no subject has yet addressed us with a complex and serious project in this field," says his statement for Mobil.cz Vlastimil Sršeň from the Press Department of Telefónica O2.
Other providers also refer to the specificity of the Czech market.
T-Mobile Press Speaker Martina Kemrová adds in rare accordance with the O2 statement: "Until now, we have not found a viable and mutually beneficial project on which to build."
And she adds: "In the network of T-Mobile, hardly a virtual provider will appear until the end of the year.
At this moment we should have a concrete offer in order to be able to think in the short term."
Vodafone focuses its attention more on meeting the requirements of its own 3G license.
Miroslav Čepický says: "For negotiations with potential virtual providers, we are open, especially in the area of cost sharing and infrastructure.
This is precisely what we consider to be the best from the customers' point of view.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is looking for a partner to build a shared network for a fast mobile Internet."
The responsible authorities - with the suppliers hand in hand
The way mobile operators operate is easy to understand, another provider was called more competition, this would lead to lower prices and thereby to a decline in profits.
So why should one make market entry easier for such a competitor?
The fact that suppliers can pull a string when it comes to something, also the long way around the origin of U:fon.
Probably the strongest pressure towards ČTÚ was at the time when U:fon came onto the market, from the company T-Mobile.
This also proves the publicly accessible information from the ČTÚ websites.
Now, however, U:fon is suitable as an argument why you should not allow a virtual provider.
Martina Kemrová commented: "The competitive environment of the mobile communications market was also recently strengthened by the entry into the market of a fourth mobile service provider.
Given the nature of the mobile communications market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that a new player in the market itself and, above all, his services would impose high requirements."
However, in view of this approach of mobile operators, the absolute disinterest of the Czech regulatory authorities surprises.
This is not just the position of the ČTÚ, which unfortunately - unlike the United Kingdom and other highly developed countries - has no competence to intervene in economic competition.
It only owns the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (ÚOHS).
This, however, refers to this whole problem of its very typical attitude.
"The entry into the market of a virtual mobile service provider would then be possible after a contract has been concluded between a mobile service provider and a virtual provider on the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
So far no such contract has been concluded, because the offer of potential prospective customers was probably not sufficiently interesting for the classic providers," said Kristián Chalupa in his reply to our request from the department of external relations of the ÚOHS.
Such a formulation would not be surprising by suppliers' representatives.
This is more than worrying from an authority representing consumer interests and, among other things, to ensure that no one abuses its position on the market.
In particular, if Kristián Chalupa adds: "Foreigners, where virtual providers work quite normally, it can be observed that their entry into the market has contributed to a price reduction in mobile telephone services."
However, the pressure on the proper functioning of the market and price reduction are probably not among the interests of the ÚOHS.
Indeed shocking in this case is the almost already touching harmony of the three mobile operators, which results from their reactions.
The question of whether this is really just a coincidence is obvious.
Just as the absolutely same fuel price at the petrol stations is surely only coincidence and the result of a hard competition.
"In this case, the Authority has not discovered any signs of action directed against competition, and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the providers have a dominant market position, so it does not have the corresponding increased responsibility for its market behaviour.
The necessary instruments for opening up the mobile market for virtual operators are probably also missing from the regulatory authority for telecommunications," explained Chalupa in his statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of many controversial points.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets, prepared by the ČTÚ, after which telecommunications is a single market from the point of view of economic competition.
On such a market, of course, none of the Czech mobile operators will have a dominant position.
However, some legal experts offer a different view - the consent of the network operator is always necessary for the market entry of a virtual provider.
And the mobile service provider - logically - has the monopoly for its network.
This means that it necessarily takes a dominant position in a particular segment.
Even if you don't go along with this argument, it should be a warning for the ÚOHS at least that three mobile operators are acting similarly.
In doing so, complaints from a number of interested parties (including the mentioned company GTS Novera) prove that they face very similar obstacles in negotiations with all suppliers.
The shifting of responsibility to the ČTÚ is then a fairly common trick in the telecommunications services, with which the ÚOHS distances itself from the whole matter.
This has been observed in a number of similar cases.
Unfortunately, in the recent amendment of the Telecommunications Act, it has not been possible to enforce the extension of ČTÚ's competences in the field of economic competition in telecommunications, although a number of experts have promised to improve the situation.
The representatives of the ÚOHS need to know all too well, but they probably have other interests.
It's all right when no one's looking.
The functioning of any pseudo-virtual provider, of which there are several equal numbers in the Czech mobile networks, remains disregarded.
There are companies that issue their own price lists for mobile telecommunications services, but are only partially public.
Normally these are companies that act in the field of multi-level marketing.
Private mobile phone services offer, for example, Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and others.
The price lists of these companies usually only reach the selection.
The joke of the matter is that the company appears to the operator as a classical company customer who orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As an important customer, he then receives special offers (and other offers).
The problem is that the terms and conditions of all Czech mobile communications providers prohibit similar types of resale.
"If there are cases you describe, then it may be a violation of the contractual conditions with which we will then deal with what might lead to an end to cooperation with the corresponding society," answered Martina Kemrová on our question on this issue.
It is quite unlikely, however, that this is not the case with those responsible for the mobile service providers.
In particular, in the case of the three companies mentioned, it can be thousands of customers.
However, no operator opposes such action.
In fact, from the activities of these companies they are not subject to negligible profits, at the same time they are not affected by the actual official marketing, unlike the actual virtual providers.
Miroslav Čepický draws attention to possible problems: "The law allows such kinds of speculation, despite all that, the services of these companies are used only by a very small percentage of customers.
Furthermore, they must accept that the SIM card does not run on their name on their phone, so they cannot have full value of it as the normal customers of mobile operators."
The ČTU should at least seem strange to the ČTÚ alone.
A further question for the ÚOHS is also raised.
The mobile operators close their eyes before such a procedure, why are they blocking themselves against a virtual provider?
It is added that the ÚOHS has quite strong competences to discover such activities, and if it does not want to, it does not have to be satisfied with the provider's statement, they did not know anything about it and their terms and conditions would prohibit it.
When Czech Republic Is Not the Most Tallest
As already stated in the text several times, the market entry of virtual suppliers resulted in a significant price decrease in the various services.
Practically in all countries, where virtual suppliers have emerged, the classic suppliers have tried to prevent their origin from occurring virtually more or less.
The arguments used by them were practically identical - a market too small or too much saturated, problems in the quality of services, etc.
In the advanced countries, however, the regulatory bodies were taking action at these moments, not trying to safeguard the interests of mobile operators, but rather their customers.
If it was through formal measures or non-formal pressure, they reached that the first virtual operator was born, and this followed further.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulators are throwing themselves at the whole case like a hot potato.
Based on our experience, we cannot escape the impression that in these cases ambiguity in the competences is more than favorable.
But let's not throw the flange into the grain.
If the background information is correct and a virtual provider is soon to appear, the Czech mobile communications market may be moving again soon.
If a provider allows the emergence of a virtual mobile service provider, the ÚOHS will not remain inactive when it comes to rejecting (discriminating) other interested parties.
And the Czechs will then no longer be making more expensive calls than the rest of Europe.
