The Prague transport companies transport on Wednesday for the first time also on a chip
Wednesday, October 1st, 2008, will enter the history of Prague's transport operations as a date on which the first passengers will enter a subway, tram or bus carrying an electronic coupon in the bag instead of a paper ticket.
These can currently buy about a hundred thousand people who own the Opencard chip card.
The passengers can buy a 30-day ticket, a 90-day ticket or an annual coupon (valid from 1 January 2009) and have it recorded on their chip card at the same time, in the information centres and branches of the traffic stations at the Muzeum metro stations, Můstek, Nádraží Holešovice, Anděl, Roztyly, Letňany, Kobylisy, Rajská zahrada, Kačerov and Luka.
Since yesterday, the coupons have also been available via the Internet on the pages of the transport companies www.dpp.cz.
The service was used by more than four hundred customers until the afternoon hours.
Those who use the internet sales can really forget the output window in the subway stations, where they have had to wait regularly in long queues for their paper licenses.
You buy the Coupon over the Internet, it is played on the Opencard in one of the thirteen branches of the city library.
"There is also a switch with trained staff available at these locations, which advises interested parties on the purchase of the Internet and also puts the coupon on the map," said the project's spokesman Martin Opatrný.
In addition to the libraries, you can also play electronic coupons on self-service machines on the opencard, which are mounted in some underground vesicles.
What do such machines look like?
They are red, remember to be lighter, the passengers may have already noticed in the metro stations Roztyly, Budějovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská.
"At present there are five of them in the city, but until the end of the year it should be eighty," adds Opatrný.
The coupon controls an automatic machine instead of the driver
The operation of the machines that will work from tomorrow on is simple.
All you have to do is insert the chip card, and the previously purchased coupon will play itself.
The electronic coupons will apply from tomorrow not only in the capital, but also in the surrounding area.
So in the suburban trains and on the bus lines with numbers 300 to 499, with which the inhabitants of the municipalities of the Central Bohemian region came to the capital.
"In the trains that belong to the Prague integrated traffic, the train attendants have readers with whom they can check the validity of the coupons after time and zone," explains Filip Drápal of the Ropid organization the ticket control. This organization compiles the timetables for Prague's transport operations.
The suburban buses have card readers at the checkout at the driver's office.
When entering, the chip card must not only be shown to the driver, but the open card must be placed in a marked position on the side of the ticket.
The driver thus controls the validity of the played coupons.
"If a passenger wants to check the validity of the played coupons, nothing is easier than asking the driver to ask for this information," Drápal says.
A passenger who does not drive with suburban buses and no longer knows when the validity of the coupon ends can, in turn, go to the self-service machines where the coupons are played on the card.
The information on the validity of his documents is displayed on the display of the device.
