Among scientists, for years a mysterious phenomenon has caused confusion - the swing-by-anomaly.
The Swing-by is a flight maneuver of space probes in which they receive additional momentum in the gravitational field of a celestial body, such as the Earth.
This allows the probes to save a lot of fuel.
The European-American research probe Cassini-Huygens used this physical trick as well as the sun probe Ulysses.
However, what the researchers have been wondering for years: the missiles do not behave 100 percent the way they would expect under the old-fashioned gravitational law.
Instead, there are irregularities in speed.
The probes are unexpectedly getting faster or slower.
So far, physicists have not been able to explain this effect.
They baptized him, Swing-by-Anomaly.
Some experts fear that maybe even the general theory of relativity of Albert Einstein, which describes the attraction of matter through a curvature of space, could not be quite right.
The American physicist Stephen Adler of the Princeton Institute for Advanced Study still firmly believes that Einstein was not mistaken, and tries to explain the swing-by anomaly with the so-called dark matter that astronomers have formed in the universe.
"Desponsible for the anomaly could be dark matter, which could also be very close to the earth," he writes.
The space scientists have only known about the existence of the dark matter for about ten years.
It is obviously an attraction whose effect on other celestial bodies can be observed.
It itself, on the other hand, is completely invisible, i.e. it sends and reflects no electromagnetic radiation, especially no visible light.
According to the scientists' calculations, the dark matter makes up well one-fifth of the entire mass of the universe.
