Isabel Bayón calls back the memory of the dancer from Seville Tórtola Valencia
A flamenco dancer from Seville honors a dancer who also dates from Seville.
Carmen Tórtola Valencia: her father was Catalane (Florenç Tórtola Ferrer) and the mother Andalusian (Georgina Valencia Valenzuela), she was born in the Triana district and when she was three years old, her family moved to London.
She was a dancer and expert on oriental dances.
She had an exciting life, she was one of the first fighters to emancipate the woman, such as Isadora Ducan, Virginia Woolf or Sarah Bernhardt.
She was Buddhist, vegetarian, and sat down for the abolition of the corset, which restricted the free female movement.
The life of this woman, who left her tracks in the dance and aesthetic revolution in Europe between the wars, fascinated Isabel Bayón.
`I wanted to work with Pepa Gamboa and she suggested this role, which seemed impossible to me.'
`We're not trying to tell about her life without keeping her Esprit,' said the flamenco dancer.
Their dance bases have helped me a lot in Flamenco.
`The dance of the butterfly' appeared to me, for example, like Guajira, or `the dance of the snake' like Tango.
Her dancing was sensual and I was told that my dancing is also in this aesthetic area', she claims.
The staging is based on two extraordinary collaborations: Miguel Poveda, who will sing to Isabel in one of her performances, as he did in 'La puerto aberetta'; and with Flamenco Master Matilde Coral, who, exceptionally, wanted to work with one of her ex-girlfriends.
`Matilde plays Tórtola, a very mature personality.
I am happy because she agreed to participate in my work, and I feel very honored.'
The staging also counts with musical composition and the guitarists Jesús Torres and Paco Arriaga, with the vocals of Miguel Ortega, el Pulga and Moi de Morón; with the percussion of El Pájaro, as well as the viola of Rafa el Viola and the collaboration with actor Juanfra Juarez, he `takes over the role of the companion of the artists who were Divas into which he is always in love.'
This work also tells in a certain way about the life of this woman, who has become known in as far away as India, the United States or Russia and also throughout Europe, although she has usually lived in London.
'I wanted to call them back in memory, because I think it is one of the women who has an enormous influence on a particular epoch and whose works no longer appreciate them,' says Bayón.
The performance takes place today at 20:30 at the Theater Lope de Vega.
