Reason - From the blood that has become safe again
Hema-Quebec celebrated yesterday's 10th anniversary of her founding, and her president, Dr. Francine Décary, had every reason to rejoice, because Hema-Quebec has become one of the safest and most efficient blood banks in the world.
And above all, it regained public confidence, which had been severely shaken by the scandal of contaminated blood in the 1980s and 1990s.
As we know, the national blood reserves managed by the Canadian Red Cross's blood supply during the 1980s were contaminated with the HI virus and the hepatitis C virus.
In view of this drama and public dissatisfaction, the Canadian Government launched in February 1994 a public investigation initiated by the judge Horace Krever aimed at bringing light to the circumstances that had led to such a tragedy and drafting guidelines to prevent a further disaster of this kind.
While judges still hesitated to report, several provinces then put a committee on the legs whose goal was to develop a new system for the management of blood preserved in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee fulfilled this mission.
According to the reports by Gélineau and Krever, two blood banks were established in Canada: Hema-Quebec, which is responsible for Quebec, and the Canadian blood company to provide the other provinces and the two territories.
`1998, when Hema-Quebec took up her work, hardly 38% of the people had confidence in the blood - preservation system in Quebec, Dr. Décary recalls.
The situation was discouraging.
Through the enormous efforts to improve the safety of blood preserves and through working in this field during the following years, we have regained public confidence', she says, before she proudly stresses that by the beginning of 2008, almost 94% of the population of Quebec now had confidence in Hema-Quebec.
Dr. Décary, however, keeps in mind that ‘confidence is something extremely fragile’.
Since its founding on 28 September 1998, Hema-Quebec has acted in accordance with the principle of caution.
At that time, we experienced the occurrence of numerous cases of the human form of cattle madness in Europe, a new type of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, this woman, who has been in charge since the founding of 1998.
`And we did not have the slightest idea whether this disease could be transmitted over the blood.
So we called on one of the main directives of the reports of Krefter and Gélineau, which according to exclusion measures are used if one does not know this and if a disease only progress slowly, as is obviously the case with Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is expressed by a degeneration of the brain, which inevitably leads to death.
So in April 1999, no blood was taken from people who had been in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980.
Well, a few years ago, without any doubt, this disease was proven to be transmitted through the blood.
So this event has shown us that the principle of caution that we used has a lot of meaning.
In 1999, a much more precise technique for the detection of HIV appeared on the market: the nucleic acid tests (NST), which enable it to demonstrate directly in the donor's blood the presence of the virus itself, and not that of the antibody against the virus, as was the case with the tests used so far.
The NST made it possible to shorten the incubation period, which takes place between the time the person was infected and when the first viruses can be detected by our techniques in the blood, the specialist explains.
This time could be reduced to a duration of less than a week.
Thus, the risk that some donors could be infected without knowing it and that this could not be recognized has been significantly reduced.
These improvements made it possible to significantly reduce the risk of transferring AIDS through blood transfusions.
Today, one in 12 million people is at risk of contracting HIV-infected blood.
`In other words, you have to distribute 12 million blood cans before someone is infected with HIV.
Since Hema-Quebec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood cans each year, it would take more than 24 years before a case of HIV transmission through a blood can.
I believe that today you can feel comfortable getting or writing a blood transfusion to restore health," says the director of Hema-Quebec.
`Our challenge for the next ten years is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know which pathogen can get into the system.
Only last year the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted through the blood by insects.
We have to monitor it continuously', Dr. Décary continues before she emphasizes that Hema-Quebec must also provide adequate care in addition to a safe supply.
`The need increases because the population ages.
As cancer control treatments are more aggressive, patients often need new red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also affects the blood donor network, of which on average only 3% belong to the blood donor population of Quebec. '
Every healthy person who is 18 years of age or older and meets the fitness criteria can donate blood every 56 days, six times a year.
On average, 14% of those who make their blood available are not accepted because they are sick, for example, of AIDS or malaria, and those who have travelled to a country where malaria is spread are excluded from blood donation for a year.
`With this 3%, we are able to obtain an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
Missing stocks are very rare.
But you have to renew the members of this donor network when they get older and they can no longer donate blood.
It's hard to convince people to donate blood, but above all, to keep them and to make them become regular donors.
Today, life is so hectic that you rarely find time to spend an hour while donating blood," regrets Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of 297 million dollars, Hema-Quebec provides not only blood preserves, but also human tissues, including bone transplants, heart valves, eye valves and skin, which are used almost exclusively for severe burns.
These tissues are examined, processed and frozen before being stored at Hema-Quebec, which also manages the only public umbilical blood bank in Quebec.
In the umbilical cord, formerly considered biomedical waste, there is rich blood on stem cells that can serve to treat severe diseases such as leukemia.
`A few weeks ago we celebrated the storage of our thousandth umbilical cord blood sample, and we plan to reduce more than a thousand yearly.
`We should probably start at the beginning of next year with making it available for transplants', explains Dr. Décary, who describes this program of cord blood loss as very popular.
`Many mothers are convinced not to have access to it,' because Hema-Quebec lacks the means to offer this complex and costly program in all Quebec hospitals.
