The psychology of overboarding - or why we are willing to pay more
In auctions, buyers tend to spend more and overvalue the bidder.
Neurologists and business researchers from the University of New York have now succeeded in discovering the neurological and economic foundations of this well-known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to a study published in the Science magazine, people want not to give in to competition, such as an auction on eBay, and are therefore willing to pay even higher prices.
The researchers have tried to explore the neurological scheme of this "game" with experimental auctions.
A group of volunteers should play Lotto while the others participated in a playful action - in both cases the active brain regions of the subjects were investigated using functional magnetic resonance (fMRI).
In both games the participants were able to win money, but an increased activity of the striatum, a complex below the brain drain, was measured in the losers of the auction, where the enemy's bid was played an essential role.
In addition to many other functions, this brain region is responsible for the "self reward" of the nervous system.
The researchers therefore felt that the price increase could be explained by avoiding overreaction of the stratum.
In order to underpin their thesis, the economists in the research group have additionally commissioned investigations to track the money.
In this case, three groups should participate against one partner under different conditions.
The control group was informed of the true value of the product, after which they made their efforts.
Another group were also promised a 15 dollar reward, in case they emerge as winners from the game.
The third group received 15 dollars before the auction, which were also lost in the event of a lost game.
So the difference between both groups was only that the emphasis on winning was on winning while the other was on losing.
However, as evidence of the hypothesis expressed by neurologists, the members of the "against losing" group were prepared for higher efforts than those of the control or "profit" group.
"These results cannot be derived from any previous economic theory.
These have so far only justified the behaviour observed in auctions with the joy of winning or avoiding risk.
The contradiction between these two theories was resolved thanks to the imaging neurological procedure, so that we now have a third explanation" - said Andrew Schotter, Professor of the Economic Faculty of the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When to seek medical advice?
Around half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary this chronic liver disease is listed among the leading causes of death.
The number of people infected in this country is estimated at one hundred thousand, but only seven thousand are treated, which is because the patients often do not know that they are infected.
Hepatitis is the term used for infectious liver diseases caused by various viruses.
The symptoms are often similar - liver inflammation and jaundice are common, but the pathogens and the diseases are different.
Depending on the pathogen, the hepatitis viruses spread in two different ways: hepatitis A and E through the digestive tract (e.g. by contaminated food or water), hepatitis B, C and D can transmit viruses through blood and other body fluids (e.g. sperm, epithelial secretion or saliva).
Travellers are recommended to vaccination against viruses A and B, there is no vaccine against virus C.
The symptoms of hepatitis A show about two to three weeks after consumption of the contaminated food and are generally accompanied by discomfort, weakness, abdominal pain and vomiting.
After that, the jaundice occurs on the skin and in the eyes, the chair becomes bright, the urine darkens, and recovery may take up to two-three weeks.
Worldwide, about 1 million people die every year from hepatitis B, far more serious diseases such as liver cancer and liver cirrhosis.
The main reason for this is that estimates suggest that only every 10th infected person is in drug treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have serious consequences: it can lead to liver cirrhosis and liver cancer.
Most infected people don't even know about their disease, because the pathogen destroys the liver cells in a frightful way - in many cases the first symptoms appear after 20-30 years.
Therefore, timely prevention, such as regular control investigations, is essential.
There are three groups in which this disease occurs more often: those who have undergone blood transfusions before 1991, drug addicts, and tattooed.
Currently, the number of chronic hepatitis C patients worldwide is estimated to be 200 million.
As the disease is already detectable in a routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to consult the home doctor at the first signs of unknown origin.
At the right time, the disease is curable, the virus can be eradicated, which prevents the risk of infection and prevents cancer.
September 30 is the World Day of Hepatitis, 2004 organized for the first time by patient representatives worldwide.
The aim of the action is to strengthen awareness for this chronic liver inflammation caused by viruses, its origin and the importance of early detection.
