Intelligent car mimics the flight of the Hummel
What would be the best way to develop new technologies to avoid accidents if not to imitate the nature of the obstacle sensors?
For example, the bees.
At CEATEC in Japan, an amazing project was presented that inspired the Nissan engineers from Hummeln to create new accidents of avoiding systems.
In collaboration with Tokyo University, Nissan has built the BR23C biomimetic system, controlled by Autorobots, a mini-car, equipped with the characteristics of the bees, with the aim of supporting the development of a system that avoids any collisions.
In flight, each bee forms its own, oval "private area", which is very similar to our own "protective shield", said Kazuhhiro Doi, product manager for technology PR and research development, at the exhibition.
The composite eye of the bee, which can see in each direction and at an angle of over 300 degrees, plays an important role in this.
In order to imitate the function of the compound eye, the researchers picked up the idea of the laser-controlled distanceometer.
This identifies obstacles to the BR23C in a 180 degree field of vision within 2 meters, calculates their distances and sends signals to the microprocessor on board, which immediately initiates the collision avoiding process.
The obstacle is recorded in seconds, and the autorobot immediately changes the course, similar to the movement of the bees, by turning the tyres around the corresponding angle.
Unlike previous systems, this maneuver takes place purely instinctively.
"If this were not the case, the autobot could not react quickly enough to avoid the obstacles," explained Toshiyauki Andoh, head of the Mobility Laboratory and Autobot project.
The system must react instinctively and immediately, as this technology corresponds to the innermost and most vulnerable part of the protective shield - a layer within which accidents are still considered unavoidable.
The whole process must reflect the behavior of the bees if they avoid other bees.
And that must be in the fraction of a second.
However, in contrast to the bees, the deviation can not be done up, down, or even diagonally - it can be only two-dimensional, only in the direction of the wearability of the tyres.
While the bees here are infinitely open to avoid other bees, the researchers were able to use only the rotational movement, or the acceleration and braking of the autobot.
The BR23C contains lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and more energy efficient, and therefore have a longer lifetime than conventional lithium ion batteries.
Andoh explained that it depends on the instinctive, intelligent response, and less on the processing of the data, and even less on the ability to store it.
This device only has to process a few inputs per second and react accordingly to them.
It does not have to store it, or by previous maneuvers produce an intuitive, logical reaction, so that it constantly takes only a handful of KB Memory.
There is no need for gigabyte and megabyte heavy memories.
This is the first step in the development of the immediate collision prevention technology, which, according to Nissan, will be in production serially within the next ten years.
Another application could find the technology in GPS satellite navigation by deliberately directing the driver around obstacles and thus leading him to the target.
