Students victims of up to 900 euros per room high rental prices
The market for apartments for students does not know any crises.
According to the last study by Sunia, the rental agency, a single room can cost a student up to 900 euros in Milan, 700 in Florence, 650 in Naples and 600 in Rome.
"This phenomenon has already taken on very serious trains. All the crowds of students lose their right to study as effectively as their families are not able to support them at this level" – says Sunia, Laura Mariani, responsible – "in these cities, the huge demand from the students leads to a deformation of the market, which has also damaged the other inhabitants.
In addition, most rental offers include a number of violations: free contracts, missing registrations, no rental price limit, unauthorized sub-lets.
For the Sunia, there is a need for exceptional measures which lead to a revision of taxation at lower rental prices.
With a closer look at the study, it turns out that in Milan a sleeping space is needed in the Brianza district about 450 euros; a single room starts at 650 euros (in the Nre Bande quarter) and ends at 800 euros in the Lambiate, Udine and Fiera district or even 900 euros in the Vittoria district.
In Florence, sleeping space costs an average of 350/400 euros, one room 700.
In Bologna, where students concentrate in the neighborhoods around the university, 250/280 euros are needed for a sleeping space, 370 to 500 for a single room.
In Rome, the prices in the neighborhoods around the university are around 600 euros for a single room, 450 for a sleeping place in a double room.
Only a little deeper are the rents in the neighborhoods around the other universities of Rome: 550 euros in Ostiense and Cinecittà.
Only those in the outside district can save money: 300 euros for a sleeping place and 450 euros for a single room in Prenestina, Centocelle and similar quarters.
In Naples you need 300-450 euros for a sleeping place, for a room the price is between 400 and 600 euros in the most expensive neighborhoods, the Policlinico, Vomero and Colli Aminei.
In Bari there is a sleeping area of 250-350 euros, a single room at least 350.
In the smallest cities prices are lower, but they have a greater weight in the urban economy.
In the cities where renting to non-European students is more frequent, such as Perugia, there is even another anomaly: a rent of 25-30% above average is required by foreign students.
Goodbye to the old cinema Paradiso – the cities close their historic cinema halls
The historical cinemas close due to the favored multiplex kinos.
"A city without cinemas is a blind city, like a face without eyes."
This picture of director Giuseppe Tornatore describes with effect what is currently happening in the major urban centers of Italy, and also in the provinces.
The process of exclusion of cinemas, which began with the birth of the large multi-sale complexes in the periphery, means in the long run death for the single cinema in the center. A process that not only appears irrevocable and irrevocable, but also carries the traits of a cultural crime.
The most affected are historical places full of memories, "it's like losing a friend with whom one has put a piece of road full of emotions", says the director of the film "Nuovo Cinema Paradiso", who brought him the Oskar and the big prize of Cannes 20 years ago. It's the story of a suburban cinema and its nostalgia, which consists of living in a probably lost cinema world.
The figures supplied by Anec, the central business association, speak a clear language: over the past five years, the enormous amount of 316 traditional cinemas have had to be closed; most of this was paid by cinemas in the major cities: 10 in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 in Turin and 5 in Palermo.
Among the most affected regions are Emilia Romagna with 82 lost cinemas, followed by Tuscany with 44 and Lombardy with 41.
This shows that the main blame is the multiplex kinos, because it is precisely these three regions in which the largest number of modern cinemas has been recorded: with 195 in the last 5 years Lombardy leads the lists, 81 are in Tuscany as well as Emilia-Romagna.
"The business has developed in an irrational way," says Paolo Protti, president of Anec, "it is useful that new structures also arise, but first of all, the preservation of the already existing one, because closes a hall in the city, not all of its regular customers are willing to look for a multiplex cinema in periphery instead of the old one.
And here is the lack of a budget for the trade union fund out of consideration: the debt burden recorded by the state is about 10 million euros.
It is a disgrace from the ethical moral point of view that the government does not respect the existing laws.
In order to preserve the sector, between 16 and 18 million euros would be needed per year".
Interestingly, the case of Bologna, the first Italian city, which, because of its fears, decided to protect it through an agreement between the municipality and the Anec; it is the first agreement of this kind in Italy to protect and support traditional cinemas, both in the historical centre and in the periphery.
Under the measures envisaged, tax incentives are also available for the cinema operators, as well as benefits for the public in terms of public transport: it will be allowed to travel to the restricted areas of the centre and also to park at cheaper parking fees.
"It is a happy initiative," says Giuseppe Tornatore, "I hope that other cities will join our example and also design new concepts.
But certainly we also need a better audio and video equipment to gear up against the superpower of the multiplex rooms, because finally the audience today is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema has always been an important topic for me: the closing of Baghiera's "supercinema", the place of my childhood and youth, was the decisive point that led me to establish the "nuovo cinema paradiso", even though I have been playing with the thought for 10 years.
For 25 years I have lived in Rome; when I pass the Rialto or the Quirinale in Via Nazionale, where I have experienced so many different emotions, I turn aside to not have to see the dust-covered posters.
