When the energy comes out of the waves, the big ones suddenly run up
It is an unsailing source of money, which covers over 70% of the planet's surface and only now seems to understand the great energy companies of the world.
Waves, currents and tides are the new renewable energy sources that are now all looking at, and are also looking for occupiers, such as giants like Chevron.
The possibility of extracting energy from the movements of the sea has been considered and investigated for 70 years; not by chance, these studies have intensified considerably since the first oil crisis.
As the oil price broke down around 1980, the idea of marine energy is being fuelled, but now the environmental organizations and the increased oil price are pushing for new impetus in this sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimates that 15% of the global energy demand could be covered by the energies generated by ocean waves.
This would be equal to the double of the energy currently produced by nuclear power plants.
In addition, the currents and tides were added.
Giants at the attack.
The first company that now relies on marine energy is Enersis, who signed a contract for the construction of a power plant in northern Portugal in 2005.
When this message was published, it seemed to be a revolutionary step.
Two years later, there are now more and more companies from the traditional energy sector that are focusing on marine energy production.
"Chevron examines these technologies" – according to the spokesman of a company known to the American giant in the Wall Street Journal – and weighs the possibility of working with us."
This is about obtaining approval from the American Energy Commission, which is necessary to start a project off the coast of Alaska.
This is not an underestimating sign, i.e. considering that oil is still being promoted by the US in Alaska and President Bush recently started the plans for new drilling.
In addition to Chevron, the companies Verdant Power Inc. from New York and Ocean Power from New Jersey, which invest in the new industry, are also not known, so observers speak of increasing interest.
Even better technologies.
Experts speak of a technology still in its wake, not least because the last doubts have not yet been clarified by the environmentalists.
So far, projects such as those in Portugal and Scotland are of a rather small scale and do not seem to cause any serious ecological problems.
However, in order to produce energy on a large scale, there is a need for technologies with far greater impact on the environment.
There are different options: Ocean Power uses a system of interconnected buoys for example.
The push of the waves, which move the buoys up and down, is converted into hydraulic pressure within the swimmer via pistons and cylinders.
This drives a turbine, which in turn operates a generator.
The electricity will be sent to the coast via underwater pipelines.
So far, there are four planned installations of this kind, which are only waiting for state approval. Part of the energy obtained could also serve for military facilities.
In fact, Verdant Power already produces energy for a department store and a parking lot with the help of underwater turbines in the East River of New York.
The water movement during the tides drives the turbines, which feed the generator through the resulting rotational movement.
According to Verdant, a long queue of potential clients is already waiting for the necessary authorizations to use these energy sources.
First the waves, then the tides.
According to the Institute for Electricity Generation Research, a particular interest is immediately earned the potential that is present in the tides.
Although it is also an irregular phenomenon, the tides are more predictable than wind currents, solar radiation and waves, and therefore a more trustworthy source of electricity.
It is precisely tidal energy that led states such as New York, Maine and Alaska as well as other coastal states to invest already $7.5 million in 2008 – up to 35 million have been planned for 2009.
